Movie: I Don't Belong Anywhere: The Cinema of Chantal Akerman

Review: It's at the point where Harold first buys the hearse that you get the sense that Hal Ashby must have been a huge influence for Wes Anderson (googled later and found out that yes). The colors and symmetry were later tip-offs. Either way I loved some of the little nudges like the editing when Maude is talking about how she loves to watch things grow, how things change into something else completely, which is divided by a cut. Or when…

lots of meaningful gazes, the tension was so high in the beginning and ending scenes but I felt there were too many "longer sequences" in the middle. Everything was shot beautifully - I especially liked the colors and framing of the "late night at nyt photo department" scene. I thought (and expected, in terms of Cate Blanchett) both of them acted really well - wasn't sure how Rooney Mara was gonna be but I think she played the role perfectly. Every year a film comes out that uses color really well and I think this was that film for 2015. Also, their clothes (!)
I love it when films capture ~that feeling~

I love Bill Hader, proved he can play a leading man, made me want to watch the Skeleton Twins. Amy Schumer is good at making funny faces to react to things. Most of this movie is her setting up scenes after which she can make those faces.
